hands_on_practices.problem:
A thin, homogeneous membrane lies in the $x$–$y$ plane and conducts a dissolved species solely by diffusion (no convection, no reaction, isothermal). The membrane exhibits anisotropic mass diffusivity described, in the fixed laboratory basis $\{\hat{\boldsymbol{i}},\hat{\boldsymbol{j}}\}$, by the symmetric, positive-definite second-order tensor
$$
\boldsymbol{D} \;=\;
\begin{pmatrix}
1.6 \times 10^{-10} & 0.7 \times 10^{-10} \\
0.7 \times 10^{-10} & 2.4 \times 10^{-10}
\end{pmatrix}
\;\; \text{m}^{2}\,\text{s}^{-1}.
$$
The solute concentration field is steady with a uniform gradient of magnitude $G = 4.0 \times 10^{3}$ $\text{mol}\,\text{m}^{-4}$ oriented at $\theta = 35^{\circ}$ from the $x$-axis in the $x$–$y$ plane, so that $\nabla c$ is constant and has that orientation.

Starting only from the fundamental statement of Fick’s first law for diffusion in anisotropic media and basic vector calculus definitions, justify whether the mass flux vector $\boldsymbol{J}$ must be collinear with the concentration gradient $\nabla c$ in such a medium, and then compute the magnitude $\|\boldsymbol{J}\|$ for the given data. Express your final answer in $\text{mol}\,\text{m}^{-2}\,\text{s}^{-1}$ and round your answer to three significant figures.
